snippet.textDisplay:
Another weekend at Bernie's boring Tilke tracks, flogging this dead horse track like a badly animated corpse of a corporate shill. Tilke tracks suck, not one of them has even the slightest charm, and they will be the death of F1 unless they are abandoned as the cynical failure of a greedy old dinosaur that they are. I spent the middle hour of the race wondering how everyone was deceived by Mercedes sandbagging, but, to be fair, they did quite a good job of it over the season. I guess that they felt the need to drop the curtain of deception yesterday, likely the hubris that comes from being so superior, in the cold, corporate way that only Germans can enjoy.

Mercedes are a sharp, professional corporate giant, and they learned the art of deceit through decades of practice, including 2 world wars lost but not forgotten. They have learned the art of survival, and that includes making your rivals believe that you are on the ropes when you are secretly controlling the battle in every way. Recall the nearly consecutive employment on racedays of Hamilton's variations on the theme of "my tires are going" when it turned out to be just a ruse. Ferrari weren't so sharp, though, because they seemed to buy it at every offering, and Mercedes kept on offering.

snippet.textDisplay:
"It's been a thoroughly enjoyable season"

This commentary begins with a base lie. The season was not thoroughly enjoyable, it was mostly dull and predictable. The core attraction, the driver's championship, was essentially decided by the August break. Why do supposedly independent (from F1 management) media hacks feel the need to lie to us at all times? When Crofty says "enjoyable" maybe he means the joy he receives from his grossly overpaid position as a corporate cheerleader? I guess he's smart enough to know that he's lucky that he still doesn't have to work for a living.
What we have here is a failure to communicate. If the only commentators that FIA and Liberty are hearing is this drivel, this does not bode well for the future. F1's fan base is dwindling quickly. The old time fans hate the new cookie cutter circuits, but Liberty will stick with them, at least the ones that can pay, because they pay well and Liberty needs the money. When your biggest backers are sports betting and megacorps, losing even one sponsor can be a major blow, especially when cost in F1 are sky high. Young fans will not be interested unless they are already anoraks, and most kids have no idea what that term even means. In an era where kids can actually participate in the Esport versions of their favorite games, they are not going to get excited by the Mercedes freight train to yet another dull dual championship.

The hybrid era is a direct contradiction to the entire concept of cost control. Demanding high tech, unreliable "power units" is no way to cut costs, and neither are expensive one off flyaway races on boring tracks.

As to the constructors' championship, it was another foregone conclusion. I posted my suspicions that Mercedes would sandbag through the season, and I think that the bookends of Australia and Abu Dhabi have proven me right. This last race was such a Mercedes blowout it was shocking, and once again the Sky SPorts crew essentially remained silent. 40 seconds between Hamilton and Leclerc. That's not racing, that's not even a proper parade. The leader was never challenged at all. Yes there was some occasional scrapping for scraps in the midfield, but mostly it was the dullest parade since pseudo Santa got drunk and peed his pantsuit on the reindeer float.
